1.16.	We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the:
Inventory Committee to (i) conduct physical count of PPE to determine the existence and condition thereof; (ii) submit the RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting and property records and (iii) follow the new COA Circular 2020-006 re: Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies;
GSO to maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered;
Municipal Accountant and the GSO to reconcile the records of the Accounting Office and Property Officer on PPE; and
concerned Municipal officials to (i) exert effort in securing  titles on all lots owned by the Municipality, and (ii) recognize these in the books using the appropriate value.

4.17.	We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations that the Management:
through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;
through the ESMO, comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels and by collecting only thosegarbage that are properly segregated;
ensure that all barangays had existing and operational MRF;
recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB) policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003;
initiate the implementation of its Anti-Littering policy ordinances as provided by Section 48 thereof;
review every two years or as the need arises the Municipal Solid Waste Management Plan for the purpose of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management;
provide support to the concerned barangay for the construction of secured fence for the MRF for security, health and sanitation purposes; and
implement the  plan of issuing Citation Tickets for violators of the Municipal Environmental Code to strengthen the drive for a more aggressive solid waste management program.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the: 

(a) heads of concerned implementing offices to explain the failure to comply with the local budget circular; 

(b) (i) implement without further delay those remaining projects not completed/implemented in CY 2022; and 

(ii) continue to monitor and supervise the effective and efficient implementation of projects funded from various source agencies within the timelines of the MOA, as far as feasible; 

(c) Municipal Planning and Development Officer to update the uploaded data on the website and make the necessary posting as part of the public disclosure requirements; and 

(d) Municipal Accountant and the Treasurer to continue to be prompt in the return of excess funds to the source agencies upon completion or termination of the project.

