We commended the MDRRMC for its tireless effort to implement urgent measures and utilize resources to contain the effects and impact of COVID-19, notwithstanding the health risk they face in their day-to-day fight against the disease. However, while the primary focused is on managing the COVID-19 crisis, planning for potentially concurrent natural disasters is also crucial to ensure that the Municipality is adequately prepared for the complexities that could arise from overlapping crises.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the (a) MDRRMC to prepare and submit the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP), indicating the (i) detailed PPAs and the corresponding appropriation classified as either Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) or Capital Outlay (CO); (ii) under a separate caption, the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years for ease of monitoring of project implementation; 

(b) MDRRMC ensure that the LDRRMF be strictly utilized for the implementation of projects and activities for disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response and rehabilitation and recovery;

(c) Municipal Accountant to (i) comply with the monthly submission of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; (ii) and maintain corresponding Subsidiary Ledger for each type of Disaster Response and Rescue Equipment; and (iii) ensure that the amount and details of the unexpended balance of the LDRRMF is discussed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that the (a) management explain why the it failed to comply with some rules set by LBC 125; 

(b)  Municipal Accountant maintain a Special Account in the General Fund for the BGCM; 



(c) concerned department to update the uploaded data on the website and make the necessary posting as part of their public disclosure requirements and submit the lacking documents above-stated and henceforth, abide by and observe the existing guidelines on emergency procurements including the preparation and submission of documents for auditing purposes.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to (a) instruct concerned officials to assess its existing organizational structure so that the ideal number of plantilla personnel will be established, thereby, avoiding the hiring of excessive number of job order personnel, especially in the Office of the Vice-Mayor and the Sangguniang Bayan; and 

(b) ensure that the hiring of job order personnel be resorted to based on necessity in order to avoid waste of much needed funds, as prescribed in Section 76 of RA 7160; 


(c) strictly adhere to the policies and guidelines in the hiring of personnel under job order as provided in CSC Memorandum No. 17, s. 2002 promulgating CSC Resolution No. 02-0790 dated June 5, 2002 and d) justify why there are overlapping of duties of the job order.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
require the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct a physical count on the property, plant and equipment to determine the existence and condition of the PPEs; and (ii) submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) duly reconciled with the accounting and property records;
require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to (i) maintain subsidiary records for PPE items such as PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively, starting with current year acquisitions until all items are covered; and (ii) reconcile the respective records of the Accounting Office and Property Officer on PPE;
